@namespace DotNetCloud.Modules.Files.UI

@*
    Help content for the Files module.
    Based on docs/user/GETTING_STARTED.md.
*@

<div class="help-content">
    <section class="help-section">
        <h2 class="help-section-title">Overview</h2>
        <p>DotNetCloud Files lets you store, organize, and share files from your web browser. Upload, browse, share, and manage your files with an intuitive interface.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="help-section">
        <h2 class="help-section-title">Uploading Files</h2>
        <p><strong>Drag and drop:</strong> Drag files from your computer and drop them onto the file browser area. A progress panel shows upload status for each file.</p>
        <p><strong>Upload button:</strong> Click the <strong>Upload</strong> button in the toolbar and select files from the file picker.</p>
        <p><strong>Paste image upload:</strong> Press <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>V</kbd> to paste an image from your clipboard. The image is uploaded automatically.</p>
        <p>The upload progress panel shows per-file progress, upload speed, estimated time remaining, and pause/resume controls. You can minimize it and continue browsing while files upload.</p>
        <p>The server configures a maximum upload file size (default: 15 GB). Files exceeding this limit are rejected before any data is sent.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="help-section">
        <h2 class="help-section-title">Browsing Files</h2>
        <p>Click a folder to open it. Use the <strong>breadcrumb trail</strong> at the top to navigate back to parent folders. Click <strong>All Files</strong> in the sidebar to return to the root.</p>
        <p>Toggle between <strong>Grid view</strong> (large icons, useful for images) and <strong>List view</strong> (detailed table with name, size, date, and type).</p>
        <p>Click column headers in list view to sort by name, size, date modified, or type.</p>
        <p>Use the <strong>search bar</strong> in the toolbar to find files by name across all your files and folders.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="help-section">
        <h2 class="help-section-title">Organizing Files</h2>
        <p><strong>Creating folders:</strong> Click the <strong>New Folder</strong> button in the toolbar or right-click and select New Folder. Folders can be nested to any depth.</p>
        <p><strong>Renaming:</strong> Select a file or folder, click <strong>Rename</strong> (or right-click → Rename), enter the new name, and press Enter.</p>
        <p><strong>Moving:</strong> Select one or more files/folders and use the Move option to relocate them.</p>
        <p><strong>Favorites:</strong> Star files to quickly access them from the Favorites section in the sidebar.</p>
        <p><strong>Tags:</strong> Add color-coded tags to files for easy categorization and filtering.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="help-section">
        <h2 class="help-section-title">Sharing Files</h2>
        <p><strong>Share links:</strong> Generate shareable links with optional password protection and expiration dates. Control whether recipients can view, comment, or edit.</p>
        <p><strong>Share with users:</strong> Share files and folders directly with other DotNetCloud users on the same instance.</p>
        <p>The <strong>Shared with me</strong> and <strong>Shared by me</strong> sections in the sidebar show your shared items.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="help-section">
        <h2 class="help-section-title">Trash</h2>
        <p>Deleted files are moved to the Trash. You can restore files from the trash or permanently delete them. The trash shows a badge count in the sidebar.</p>
    </section>

    <section class="help-section">
        <h2 class="help-section-title">Tips &amp; Tricks</h2>
        <ul class="help-tips">
            <li>Use keyboard shortcuts: <kbd>Ctrl</kbd>+<kbd>A</kbd> to select all, <kbd>Delete</kbd> to move to trash.</li>
            <li>Tag frequently accessed files for quick filtering.</li>
            <li>Monitor your storage quota in the sidebar to avoid running out of space.</li>
        </ul>
    </section>
</div>
